			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2022</a> paper:</span><br><i>Gradual Grammars: Syntax in Levels and Locales</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/TijsvanderStorm.html">Tijs van der Storm</a>, <a href="../profile/FelienneHermans.html">Felienne Hermans</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3567512.3567524">10.1145/3567512.3567524</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagM">T1A: Design</span></a><ul><li> It proposes a language-design approach for grammars that vary across levels/locales.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5h.html"><span class="tagL">T5H: Usability</span></a><ul><li> The motivation is user-centered syntax design and accessibility across user groups.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> It enables integrating multiple syntactic variants within one language definition.
</li></ul></li></ul>
